==Units derived from the Hubble constant==
{{More citations needed section|date=March 2014}}

===Hubble time===
The Hubble constant &lt;math&gt;H_0&lt;/math&gt; has units of inverse time; the '''Hubble time''' ''t&lt;sub&gt;H&lt;/sub&gt;'' is simply defined as the inverse of the Hubble constant,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last1=Hawley|first1=John F.|last2=Holcomb|first2=Katherine A.|title=Foundations of modern cosmology|date=2005|publisher=Oxford Univ. Press|location=Oxford [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-19-853096-1|pages=304|edition=2nd}}&lt;/ref&gt; i.e.

:&lt;math&gt;t_H \equiv \frac{1}{H_0} = \frac{1}{67.8\textrm{(km/s)/Mpc}} = 4.55\cdot 10^{17}\textrm{s}  = 14.4 \text{ billion years}.&lt;/math&gt;

This is slightly different from the age of the universe which is approximately 13.8 billion years. The Hubble time is the age it would have had if the expansion had been linear, and it is different from the real age of the universe because the expansion is not linear; they are related by a dimensionless factor which depends on the mass-energy content of the universe, which is around 0.96 in the standard ΛCDM model.

We currently appear to be approaching a period where the expansion of the universe is exponential due to the increasing dominance of [[vacuum energy]]. In this regime, the Hubble parameter is constant, and the universe grows by a factor [[E (mathematical constant)|''e'']] each Hubble time:

:&lt;math&gt;H \equiv \frac{\dot a}{a} = \textrm{constant} \quad \Longrightarrow \quad a \propto e^{Ht} = e^{\frac{t}{t_H}}&lt;/math&gt;

Likewise, the generally accepted value of 2.27 [[Exa|Es]]&lt;sup&gt;−1&lt;/sup&gt; means that (at the current rate) the universe would grow by a factor of &lt;math&gt;e^{2.27}&lt;/math&gt; in one [[exasecond]].
